Ford GoBike Data Exploration¶

by Ayush Mathur¶

Introduction¶

A bike-share system is a service in which bicycles are made available for shared use to individuals on a short term basis for a price or free. Many bike share systems allow people to borrow a bike from a "dock" and return it at another dock belonging to the same system. Ford GoBike is a public bicycle sharing system in San Francisco Bay Area, California. currently has over 2,600 bicycles in 262 stations across San Francisco, East Bay and San Jose. As of January 2018, the system had seen nearly 500,000 rides since the launch in 2017 and had about 10,000 annual subscribers.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In this project, we are analyzing data from 2017 to July 2019.

Ford GoBike Rides per month¶

  • Frequency of rides is highest during the month of July. Followed by months of June, April, March and May.
  • Summers have the highest demand of Ford GoBike. Winters have the least number of rides. December and November having the least couny of rides.

Bike Rides hourly distribution¶

  • We have the peak hours during 8 to 9 in morning and 16 to 18 in the evening.
  • And a moderate use during the day.
  • the bikes are used during the office commute hours.

Ride variation per trip duration¶

  • Majority of the rides are for short duration but quite a few range upto 23 hours. Only about 1% of the total entries are more than an hour.
  • The highest frequency of rides is for the duration of about 5 to 6 minutes. Number of rides decreases as the trip duration increases.
  • Most trips are completed within half-an-hour.
  • Average trip duration is highest for months of August and September and least for months of January and February.
  • Average duration increases by around 2 minutes or by 15%.
  • Average trip duration increases by more than 30% on the weekend but the average distance decreases by 5%.

Customer v/s Subscriber trend over the Year¶

  • Subscribers have the similar trend as the overall trend. It is probably because the dataset is subscriber heavy.
  • Subscribers and customers both have the more number of rides in summer than winter.
  • Subscribers have peak around July whereas customers have peak in April.

Hour-Week-Monthly Distribution¶

  • 8 and 17 are the busiest hours of the day throughout the year.
  • Weekends have the minimum demand.
  • Overall peak hours of the day are 7 to 9 and 16 to 19.
  • Months from March to July receive the most demand.
  • There is some amount of demand even through the night.
  • Monday and Tuesday in July will have the highest demand.
  • Tuesday to Thursday from April to July have the overall highest demand.
  • Weekends have the least demand as well as the months of November and December.
  • Rest of the time we have moderate demand.

Distance over the year by Age groups¶

  • Mostly all the age groups show similar trends except for the teenagers(age: 10-20)
  • All groups have peaks in March whereas teenagers have peak during June-July when others have the least mean distance.
  • Users within the age group 30 to 40 have the highest mean distance.

Duration over the year by Age groups¶

  • As expected, teenagers spent most of the time on bike. During august, it is almost triple the time spent by other groups.
  • Trends for all the groups are similar except for teenagers.
  • Teenagers have the peaks in the months of August and June.

Conclusion¶

  • Age groups have had an impact. Overall mean longest trip duration in August and september is the result of sudden peak in the trip duration of teenagers during Summer. They have 3 times the duration than other age groups.
  • Other age groups have more or less similar trends overall. Therefore, a sudden rise or fall in teenagers trend has an impact on the overall trend.
  • Users within the age group 30 to 40 have the highest mean distance.
  • Average distance travelles by teenagers is less but the time spent is more. Changes in their trends in summer and winter are visible in the overall trend.
  • Gender does not seem to have an high impact on the trend.
  • Customer and subscriber trends vary but the data is subscriber heavy. Customer trends are not visible in overall trends.
